"{{Short description|none}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2024}}\n{{Politics of Somaliland}}\n'''Foreign relations of the Republic of Somaliland''' are the responsibility of the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Somaliland)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] of the [[Republic of Somaliland]].<ref name=\"ministers\">[https://archive.today/20010107213900/http://www.somalilandgov.com/government.htm Council of Ministers]. Government of Somaliland.</ref> The region's self-declaration of independence (from [[Somalia]] on 18 May 1991, after the start of the ongoing [[Somali Civil War]]) remains unrecognised by the [[international community]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/webcast/pdfs/unia991.pdf |title=UN in Action: Reforming Somaliland's Judiciary |access-date=29 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/05/world/africa/05somaliland.html |last=Lacey |first=Marc |date=5 June 2006 |title=The Signs Say Somaliland, but the World Says Somalia |website=The New York Times |access-date=25 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nDue to its status, the Republic of Somaliland currently has official contacts with only a few nations, such as [[Ethiopia]], which has signed a strategic and infrastructure agreement,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geeskaafrika.com/6468/ethiopia-somaliland-signed-strategic-trade-and-infrastructure-agreement/|title=Ethiopia: Somaliland signed strategic trade and infrastructure agreement - Geeska Afrika Online|website=www.GeeskaAfrika.com|date=19 November 2014 |access-date=12 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.geeskaafrika.com/6468/ethiopia-somaliland-signed-strategic-trade-and-infrastructure-agreement/|title=Ethiopia: Somaliland signed strategic trade and infrastructure agreement - Geeska Afrika Online|last=geeskadmin|date=19 November 2014|newspaper=Geeska Afrika Online|language=en-US|access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref> and the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE), which has signed a concession agreement to manage the [[Port of Berbera]].<ref name=\"wsj.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/dubais-dp-world-agrees-to-manage-port-in-somaliland-for-30-years-1464549937|title=Dubai's DP World Agrees to Manage Port in Somaliland for 30 Years|first1=Matina|last1=Stevis|first2=Asa|last2=Fitch|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=30 May 2016|access-date=7 December 2016|via=www.WSJ.com}}</ref> Somaliland has established [[de facto embassy|de facto embassies]] with nations such as the [[United States]], as well as [[Taiwan]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=12 April 2021 |title=Somaliland and Taiwan: Two territories with few friends but each other |language=en-GB |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-56719409 |access-date=11 August 2023}}</ref> International recognition as a [[sovereign state]] remains at the forefront of the government's current foreign policy. Other key priorities include encouraging international aid and [[foreign direct investment]].\n\nMost multilateral organisations and countries in the international community support the territorial integrity (i.e. territorial unity) of Somalia and its central government, the [[Federal Government of Somalia]] during the ongoing civil war and oppose Somaliland's secession.<ref name=\"Cosgmsos\">{{cite web|title=Communiqué on Secretary-General's Mini-Summit on Somalia|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2012/sg2187.doc.htm|publisher=United Nations|access-date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:Abdirahaamn_Abdullahi_cirro_(cropped).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The President of the Republic of Somaliland, [[Abdirahman Mohamed Abdullahi]], pushed for international recognition at the 2025 [[World Governments Summit]] held in Dubai. ]]\n[[File:Somaliland_cabinet_in_session.jpg|thumb|right|400px| President Musa Bihi leads Governmental meeting]]\n==International relations==\n[[File:Diplomatic missions in Somaliland.svg|thumb|right|350px|Map of diplomatic missions in Somaliland {{legend|#007f0f|Somaliland}} <!--{{legend|#2f3699|States with embassy in Somaliland}}--> {{legend|#709ad1ff|States with consulate or representative office in Somaliland}}  <!--{{legend|#0bd1c8ff|States with non-resident embassy to Somaliland}}-->]]\n[[File:Diplomatic missions of Somaliland.svg|thumb|right|350px|Map of diplomatic missions of Somaliland {{legend|#007f0f|Somaliland}} <!--{{legend|#2f3699|States with embassy in Somaliland}}--> {{legend|#709ad1ff|States hosting a representative office of Somaliland}}  <!--{{legend|#0bd1c8ff|States with non-resident embassy to Somaliland}}-->]]\nSomaliland has political contacts with neighbouring [[Ethiopia]]<ref name=\"Future recognition\" /> and [[Djibouti]],<ref name=\"Djibouti\" >{{cite web|title=Somaliland, Djibouti in bitter port feud|url=http://www.afrol.com/articles/23556|publisher=afrol News|access-date=22 July 2007}}</ref> as well as with [[Belgium]],<ref name=\"Future recognition\" >{{cite web|title=Somaliland closer to recognition by Ethiopia|url=http://www.afrol.com/articles/25633|publisher=Afrol News|access-date=6 July 2007}}</ref> [[Canada]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal |last=Christopher |first=Clapham |date=June 2011 |title=African Game Changer?: The Consequences of Somaliland's International (Non) Recognition |url=https://www.thebrenthurstfoundation.org/downloads/consequences-of-somalilands-international-recognition.pdf |journal=The Brenthurst Foundation}}</ref> [[France]],<ref>{{cite news|title=France recognizes ''de facto'' Somaliland|url=http://www.lesnouvelles.org/P10_magazine/15_grandentretien/15055_mahamudsalahnur_eng.html|publisher=Les Nouvelles d'Addis|date=8 April 2008|access-date=4 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715224433/http://www.lesnouvelles.org/P10_magazine/15_grandentretien/15055_mahamudsalahnur_eng.html|archive-date=15 July 2010}}</ref> [[Ghana]],<ref name=\"Future recognition\" /> [[Kenya]],<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Norway]],<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Russia]],<ref name=\"express.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/948063/russia-news-vladimir-putin-naval-base-africa-somaliland-1956-suez-crisis|title=Putin flexes muscles with plans for new African base - with chilling echoes of Suez|publisher=express.co.uk|date=18 April 2018|access-date=21 October 2018}}</ref> [[South Africa]],<ref name=\"Future recognition\" /> [[South Sudan]],<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Sweden]],<ref name=\"Future recognition\" /> the [[United Kingdom]],<ref name=\"Future recognition\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Somaliland|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmhansrd/vo040204/halltext/40204h03.htm|publisher=United Kingdom Parliament|date=4 February 2004|access-date=23 February 2007}}</ref> the [[United States]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Somaliland Liaison Office Washington DC|url=http://somalilandpress.com/press-release-the-republic-of-somailand-liaison-office-washington-dc-12868|publisher=Somaliland Liaison Office|access-date=19 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404125152/http://somalilandpress.com/press-release-the-republic-of-somailand-liaison-office-washington-dc-12868|archive-date=4 April 2013}}</ref> and [[Yemen]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2007, a delegation led by President Kahin was present at the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2007|Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]] in [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]. Somaliland has applied to join the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] under [[observer status]], but its application remains pending.<ref>{{cite web|title=Somaliland on verge of observer status in the Commonwealth|url=http://www.qarannews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6381&Itemid=59|publisher=Qaran News|date=16 November 2009|access-date=2 February 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:Montevideo_Convention_parties.svg|thumb|right|300px| Somaliland meets criteria set by Montevideo convention, as media sources state lobbying in the USA of diplomatic recognition of Somaliland as an independent country.]]\n\n\n===Africa===\nIn 2011, the foreign ministers of South Africa and [[Tanzania]] said that they would not recognise Somaliland and preferred that Somalia remained a single country.<ref>{{cite news|date=13 August 2011|title=SA, Tanzania don't recognise Somaliland|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/local/2011/08/13/sa-tanzania-don-t-recognise-somaliland|newspaper=Times Live|access-date=13 October 2014}}</ref> In 2012, South Africa and Ethiopia again re-affirmed their continued support for Somalia's government, territorial integrity, and sovereignty at the mini-summit on Somalia in New York on the margins of the United Nations General Assembly.<ref name=\"Cosgmsos\"/> However, [[South Africa]] has formally declared that Somaliland fulfils the [[Montevideo Convention]] criteria for statehood in addition to it accepting the Somaliland passport.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|last1=Hansen|first1=Stig Jarle|last2=Bradbury|first2=Mark|date=1 September 2007|title=Somaliland: A New Democracy in the Horn of Africa?|journal=Review of African Political Economy|volume=34|issue=113|pages=461–476|doi=10.1080/03056240701672585|s2cid=154448170|issn=0305-6244|hdl=10.1080/03056240701672585|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n\nThe [[African Union]] (AU) is considering Somaliland's application for membership to the bloc and has indicated a willingness to deal with it as an 'outstanding case'.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n====Ethiopia====\n{{main|Ethiopia–Somaliland relations}}\n[[Somaliland]] has had decent economic relations with [[Ethiopia]] since the [[Eritrean–Ethiopian War]], as a large part of Ethiopian exports have been handled via the port of Berbera, since [[Ethiopia]] can no longer use [[Eritrea]]n ports of [[Massaua]] and [[Assab]]. These relationships stand in contrast to the \"traditional hostility\" towards Ethiopia felt by many Somalis in other areas, and against the background of low support among many northern Somalis for [[Siad Barre]]'s [[Ogaden War]] against Ethiopia and the [[Somali National Movement]] which Ethiopia assisted financially.<ref>Maria Brons: ''Somaliland: Two years after the declaration of independence'', 1993, ISBN 978-3-928049-23-8 (S. 11, 23, 25)</ref> So far, however, these have not led to official Ethiopian recognition. On 1 January 2024, Ethiopia and Somaliland signed a [[2024 Ethiopia–Somaliland memorandum of understanding|pact]] giving Ethiopia access to the Red Sea in return for eventual recognition, making it the first UN member state to do so.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thesomalidigest.com/somaliland-and-ethiopia-recognition-for-sea-acce | title=Somaliland and Ethiopia: Recognition for Sea Access | date=January 2024 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Ethiopia signs agreement to use Somaliland's Red Sea port |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2024/1/1/ethiopia-signs-agreement-to-use-somalilands-red-sea-port |access-date=1 January 2024 |website=Al Jazeera |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/world/africa/landlocked-ethiopia-signs-pact-use-somalilands-red-sea-port-2024-01-01 | title=Ethiopia signs pact to use Somaliland's Red Sea port | newspaper=Reuters }}</ref>\n\n====Guinea====\n[[File:Muse Bihi Abdi-Mamadi Toure meeting.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|The fifth President of Somaliland, Muse Bihi Abdi, visit to the Republic of Guinea.]] In late July 2019, [[President of Somaliland|Somaliland President]] [[Muse Bihi Abdi]] led a delegation to the [[Guinea|Republic of Guinea]] at the invitation of [[President of Guinea|President]] [[Alpha Condé|Alpha Conde]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/world/africa/somaliland-rape-law-adoption|title=Somaliland MPs adopt first ever rape law|website=Rappler|date=10 January 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.horndiplomat.com/2019/07/03/somaliland-president-arrives-in-guinea-conakry-for-state-visit/|title=Somaliland President Arrives in Guinea-Conakry for State Visit|date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Kenya====\n[[File:Bihi-Kenyata meeting.jpg|thumb|President Bihi and Kenyan President, [[Uhuru Kenyatta]]]]\nIn December 2020, Kenya and Somaliland agreed that a Kenyan consulate would open in Hargeisa, and to commence direct flights between Hargeisa and [[Nairobi]], both by March 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/15/world/africa/somalia-kenya.html|title=Somalia Severs Diplomatic Ties With Kenya|work=The New York Times|date=15 December 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n====Israel====\n{{main|Israel–Somaliland relations}}\n\n[[Israel]] was one of 35 countries that recognised [[State of Somaliland|Somaliland]]'s brief independence in 1960.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bereketeab|first=Redie|url=https://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:nai:diva-1573|title=Self-determination and Secessionism in Somaliland and South Sudan: Challenges to Postcolonial State-building|date=2012|publisher=[[Nordiska Afrikainstitutet]]|isbn=978-91-7106-725-8|language=en}}</ref> However, it does not currently hold direct diplomatic ties with [[Somaliland]]. In February 2010, Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesperson Yigal Palmor was quoted in the [[Haaretz|Haaretz Daily]] that his government was ready to recognise Somaliland again.<ref>{{cite web|date=15 February 2010|title=Israel ready to recognize Somaliland|url=https://www.defenceweb.co.za/governance/governance-governance/israel-ready-to-recognize-somaliland/|access-date=13 July 2020|website=defenceWeb|language=en-ZA}}</ref><ref name=\"unpo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unpo.org/content/view/10712/236/|title=Somaliland: Israel says ready to recognize Somaliland|publisher=UNPO|date=12 February 2010|access-date=29 May 2012|archive-date=27 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200427041243/https://unpo.org/content/view/10712/236/}}</ref> However, he stated that the Somaliland government has not contacted the Israeli government to seek ties.\n\nIn 1995, former President [[Muhammad Haji Ibrahim Egal|Egal]] of [[Somaliland]] also wrote a letter to Prime Minister [[Yitzhak Rabin]] seeking to establish diplomatic ties between the two countries.<ref name=\"unpo\" /> In September 2001, it was also reported that [[Somaliland]] was looking towards Tel Aviv after Saudi Arabia banned imports of livestock from the country due to Rift Valley fever.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|date=5 February 2001|title=Somaliland 'here to stay'|language=en-GB|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/1154169.stm|access-date=13 July 2020}}</ref> During this time several Israeli businessmen were also in the nation's capital [[Hargeisa]].<ref name=\":1\" /> However, President [[Dahir Riyale Kahin|Kahin]], who succeeded [[Muhammad Haji Ibrahim Egal|Egal]], is reported to have avoided approaching Israel to prevent straining fragile relations with the [[Arab]] and Muslim world, which it heavily relies on for its livestock trade.<ref name=\"unpo\" /> In August 2020, Somaliland expressed its support for the [[Israel–United Arab Emirates normalization agreement]]. In 2024 Times of Israel media source stated that Israel's [[Somaliland]] recognition would boost security for the country, after UK/USA Planing to open representative offices in [[Hargeisa]], Somaliland's capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.busiweek.com/somaliland-joins-world-in-hailing-israel-and-uae-diplomatic-deal/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200929102354/https://www.busiweek.com/somaliland-joins-world-in-hailing-israel-and-uae-diplomatic-deal/|url-status=usurped|archive-date=29 September 2020|title=Somaliland Joins World In Hailing Israel And UAE Diplomatic Deal|website=busiweek.com|date=14 August 2020}}</ref> In March 2025 Israeli and American government officials spoke with Somaliland, as well as Somalia and Sudan regarding the resettlement of Gazans displaced by the [[2023-2025 Israel Hamas War]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=U.S., Israel Look to African Nations for Resettling Gazans |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/2025-03-14/ty-article/u-s-israel-look-to-african-nations-for-resettling-gazans/00000195-934b-d2e6-af97-d75b4f280000?utm_source=mailchimp&utm_medium=Content&utm_campaign=israel-at-war&utm_content=8766cde2a7 |website=Haaretz |date=2025-03-14 |access-date=2025-03-14}}</ref>\n====Pakistan====\nIn November 2009, a Pakistani delegation composed of Sheikh Mansoor Ahmed, Secretary General of the ruling [[Pakistan Peoples Party]], Shafiq Ahmed Qureshi, Peace Representative, former diplomat and Senior Consular Officer, and Abdul Razak Dinnaari, an ambassador, visited Somaliland and proposed the opening of a Somaliland trade office in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.somalilandcurrent.com/2009/11/08/pakistani-delegation-arrive-somaliland/|title=Pakistani Delegation Arrives In Somaliland|website=busiweek.com|date=8 November 2009|access-date=9 February 2021|archive-date=10 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210210112113/https://www.somalilandcurrent.com/2009/11/08/pakistani-delegation-arrive-somaliland/}}</ref> In February 2020, Pakistan's Look Africa Policy Initiative conference was held in Nairobi, Kenya.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.busiweek.com/pakistan-asked-to-extend-its-look-africa-policy-initiative-to-somaliland/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200929084154/https://www.busiweek.com/pakistan-asked-to-extend-its-look-africa-policy-initiative-to-somaliland/|url-status=usurped|archive-date=29 September 2020|title=Pakistan Asked To Extend Its Look Africa Policy Initiative To Somaliland|website=busiweek.com |date=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Taiwan====\n{{main|Somaliland–Taiwan relations}}\n\n[[File:Somaliland Foreign Minister Hagi Mohamoud with Taiwan President Tsai Ing-wen.jpg|thumb|Somaliland Foreign Minister [[Yasin Haji Mohamoud|Hagi Mohamoud]] with the then-President of Taiwan, [[Tsai Ing-wen]]]] In July 2020, Somaliland announced that it would establish a representative office in [[Taiwan]] (Republic of China).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|title=Taiwan Strengthens Ties With Breakaway Somaliland|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-07-01/taiwan-to-set-up-representative-office-in-breakaway-somaliland|access-date=2 July 2020|newspaper=Bloomberg|date=July 2020 }}</ref> The Taiwan Representative Office officially was established in Hargeisa the next month.<ref>{{cite web|title=台灣駐索馬利蘭代表處正式成立 雙方國旗飄揚[影] {{!}} 政治 {{!}} 重點新聞 {{!}} 中央社 CNA|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202008175006.aspx|access-date=22 August 2020|publisher=Central News Agency|website=www.cna.com.tw|date=17 August 2020 |language=zh-Hant-TW}}</ref> In August, Taiwan opened its office in Somaliland, which was reciprocated by Somaliland by opening an office in Taiwan on 9 September 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Somaliland to open office in Taiwan|date=8 September 2020|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/4004246|publisher=Taiwan News|access-date=9 September 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Turkey ====\nThough not recognising Somaliland and accrediting the building to Somalia, Turkey has an active consulate in [[Hargeisa]]. Turkey with a representative office in Hargeisa and member of Nato ,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Dışişleri'nde Somaliland skandalı|url=https://www.cumhuriyet.com.tr/haber/disislerinde-somaliland-skandali-563404|access-date=18 May 2021|website=www.cumhuriyet.com.tr|date=7 July 2016 |language=tr}}</ref> Since 2013, Turkey has been a [[Mediation|mediator]] between the Somali and Somaliland governments.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Türkiye - Somali Siyasi İlişkileri|url=https://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkiye-somali-siyasi-iliskileri.tr.mfa#:~:text=%C3%9Clkemiz%2C%201991%20y%C4%B1l%C4%B1nda%20tek%20tarafl%C4%B1,y%C4%B1l%C4%B1ndan%20beri%20kolayla%C5%9Ft%C4%B1r%C4%B1c%C4%B1%20rol%20%C3%BCstlenmi%C5%9Ftir.&text=1992%20y%C4%B1l%C4%B1ndan%20bug%C3%BCne%20kadar%2C%201.092,Burslar%C4%B1ndan%20yararlanarak%20%C3%BClkemizde%20y%C3%BCksek%C3%B6%C4%9Frenim%20g%C3%B6rm%C3%BC%C5%9Ft%C3%BCr.|website=mfa.gov.tr}}</ref> In 2019, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Somalia)|Somali Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Ahmed Isse Awad]] stated that Turkey plays a leading role in the mediation process.<ref>{{Cite web|title='Somali'nin Türkiye'den daha iyi dostu yok'|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/dunya/somali-disisleri-bakani-avad-somalinin-turkiyeden-daha-iyi-dostu-yok/1657803|access-date=18 May 2021|website=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref> Somaliland rejected the Turkeys mediation role between Ethiopia and Somalia in a seaport deal by Somaliland in 2024.{{citation needed|date=July 2025}}\n\nIn 2012, Genel Enerji, an energy company mostly owned by [[Çukurova Holding]], signed a deal with the Somaliland government to search oil reserves within the nation.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Somali'de petrol rezervi ne kadar? Erdoğan'ın 'Teklif geldi' açıklamasına Somali Petrol Bakanı ne diyor?|language=tr|work=BBC News Türkçe|url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-dunya-51210933|access-date=18 May 2021}}</ref> Genel oil blocs found major crude oil vein around 2 Barrles of crude oil in bahadhamal region of genel west bloc, Genel energy is seen as a success in Somaliland- Turkey relations.\n\n====United Arab Emirates====\n{{main|Somaliland–United Arab Emirates relations}}\n[[File:President Muse Bihi Abdi with UAE Amb. Abdulla Alnaqbi.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|right| The fifth President of Somaliland, Muse Bihi Abdi with UAE Amb. Abdulla Alnaqbi.]]\n\nIn February 2017, both houses of the [[parliament of Somaliland]] accepted the bid from the [[Politics of the United Arab Emirates|government of the UAE]] for the [[Union Defence Force (UAE)]] to establish a military base in [[Berbera]] along with the redevelopment of the Berbera Airport.<ref>{{cite web|title=Somalia: Northern Territory Approves UAE Naval Base|url=https://www.stratfor.com/situation-report/somalia-northern-territory-approves-uae-naval-base|access-date=21 March 2017|work=stratfor.com}}</ref> The [[United Arab Emirates]] has appointed a new [[representative office|representative]] to Somaliland which will be the first Arab nation to send a diplomat to Hargeisa.<ref>{{cite news|title=UAE Appoints a new representative to Somaliland|work=Somaliland Standard|url=https://somalilandstandard.com/uae-appoints-a-new-representative-to-somaliland/|access-date=13 March 2021}}</ref> On 13 March 2021, Abdulla Al-Naqbi was appointed as UAE ambassador to [[Somaliland]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Madaxweynaha Somaliland oo warqadda aqoonsiga ka guddoomay wakiilka Imaaraatka - Somali|url=http://www.bbc.com/somali/live/war-56384585|access-date=13 March 2021|website=BBC News Somali|language=so-SO}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Staff|date=13 March 2021|title=President Bihi Welcomes the United Arab Emirates Ambassador to Somaliland|url=https://somalilandchronicle.com/2021/03/13/president-bihi-welcomes-the-united-arab-emirates-ambassador-to-somaliland/|access-date=13 March 2021|website=Somaliland Chronicle|language=en-US}}</ref> In March 2025 Israeli and American government officials spoke with Somaliland, as well as Somalia and Sudan regarding the resettlement of Gazans displaced by the [[2023-2025 Israel Hamas War]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=U.S., Israel Look to African Nations for Resettling Gazans |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/2025-03-14/ty-article/u-s-israel-look-to-african-nations-for-resettling-gazans/00000195-934b-d2e6-af97-d75b4f280000?utm_source=mailchimp&utm_medium=Content&utm_campaign=israel-at-war&utm_content=8766cde2a7 |website=Haaretz |date=2025-03-14 |access-date=2025-03-14}}</ref>\n\n===Americas===\n====United States====\n{{main|Somaliland–United States relations}}\n[[File:The_Heritage_Foundation.svg|thumb|right|300px|The Heritage foundation led an article on why the USA should recognize Somaliland as an independent  country.]]\n\nSomaliland and the United States do not have official diplomatic relations. However, Somaliland operates a representative liaison office in [[Washington, D.C.]], but it does not have formal diplomatic status under the provisions of the [[Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.somalilandgov.com/contacts.htm |title=THE CONTACTS AND ADDRESSES OF THE SOMALILAND REPRESENTATIVE OFFICES AROUND THE WORLD |access-date=24 May 2010 |archive-date=27 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327105631/http://www.somalilandgov.com/contacts.htm |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref> Both countries do maintain contacts as delegations from both sides have met in the past. The U.S. policy regarding Somaliland is to first allow the [[African Union]] to deliberate the question regarding the status of Somaliland as an independent nation.\n\n[[File:Select_Committee_on_the_CCP_logo.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The select committee of the US, in competition with the People's Republic of China, stated that a representative office should be opened in Somaliland. Somaliland is a member of the [[Taiwan]] pact, and has a recognition bid based on the [[Montevideo convention]], having issued their own passports and having a diplomatic service.]] \n\nThe [[United States]] engages Somaliland on policy matters such as democratization and [[economic development]]. In 2023, the United States provided $1,000,000 in aid through the [[International Republican Institute]] to support training for parliamentarians and other key programs in preparations for the [[2010 Somaliland presidential election|2024 Somaliland presidential election]]. The U.S. expected to provide an additional $1,500,000 in continued support for the [[democratization]] process in Somaliland following the elections.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.state.gov/p/af/rls/fs/2007/96359.htm |title=United States Policy on Somaliland |access-date=10 April 2021 |archive-date=11 December 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211203321/http://www.state.gov/p/af/rls/fs/2007/96359.htm |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref> In March 2025 Israeli and American government officials spoke with Somaliland, as well as Somalia and Sudan regarding the resettlement of Gazans displaced by the [[2023-2025 Israel Hamas War]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=U.S., Israel Look to African Nations for Resettling Gazans |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/2025-03-14/ty-article/u-s-israel-look-to-african-nations-for-resettling-gazans/00000195-934b-d2e6-af97-d75b4f280000?utm_source=mailchimp&utm_medium=Content&utm_campaign=israel-at-war&utm_content=8766cde2a7 |website=Haaretz |date=2025-03-14 |access-date=2025-03-14}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n====Germany====\n{{main|Germany–Somaliland relations}}\n\nIn 2002, Germany considered recognising Somaliland and establishing a military base in the country. They did not do so and the naval base was instead established in Djibouti.<ref name=\"german-foreign-policy.com\">{{cite web|title=Deutsche Flotte bricht nach Ostafrika auf|url=http://www.german-foreign-policy.com/de/fulltext/20084|publisher=German News Information GmbH|access-date=2 May 2021|archive-date=5 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305094854/http://www.german-foreign-policy.com/de/fulltext/20084}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uni-kassel.de/fb5/frieden/regionen/Somalia/dieterich.html|title = FB 05 Gesellschaftswissenschaften}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/dschibuti-einer-der-heissesten-flecken-der-welt-1.313955 | title=Dschibuti – Einer der heißesten Flecken der Welt | publisher= Süddeutsche.de | date=2 January 2002 | access-date=2 May 2021}}</ref> [[German Navy|German naval ships]] already operated from Berbera.<ref name=\"german-foreign-policy.com\"/> In September 2012, at the mini-summit on Somalia on the margins of the United Nations General Assembly, the German government re-affirmed its continued support for Somalia's government, territorial integrity and sovereignty.<ref name=\"Communiqué\">{{cite web|title=Communiqué on Secretary-General's Mini-Summit on Somalia|url=http://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2012/sg2187.doc.htm|publisher=United Nations|access-date=7 August 2013}}</ref> In 2019, the German ambassador to Kenya and Somalia visited Hargeisa and met with [[Muse Bihi Abdi]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Somaliland President Receives German Ambassador to Kenya and Somalia|date=8 April 2019|url=https://www.horndiplomat.com/2019/04/08/somaliland-president-receives-german-ambassador-to-kenya-and-somalia/|publisher=Horn Diplomat|access-date=2 May 2021}}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{main|Somaliland–United Kingdom relations}}\n\nIn April 2014, the Sheffield City Council in the [[United Kingdom]] voted to recognise the right to self-determination of Somaliland, the second British city council to do so, after the Bristol City Council{{when|date=February 2022}}. The gesture however was ceremonial and not legally binding.<ref name=\"Vshbsfiib\">{{cite news|title=Somaliland Hails British Step Forward in Independence Bid|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/somaliland-hails-british-step-forward-in-independence-bid/1886918.html|access-date=23 April 2014|newspaper=VOA|date=5 April 2014}}</ref> On 26 March 2015, [[Cardiff Council]] followed suit<ref>{{cite web|last=Mosalski|first=Ruth|date=26 March 2015|title=Cardiff becomes the third UK council to recognise the Republic of Somaliland|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/somaliland-recognised-by-cardiff-council-8930027|access-date=21 March 2017|work=walesonline.co.uk}}</ref> and later on 18 May 2015, the UK Independence Party announced their support for the recognition of [[Somaliland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.somalilandpress.com/ukip-supports-somaliland-national-day/|title=UKIP supports Somaliland National Day|date=18 May 2015|work=somalilandpress.com|access-date=21 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626125736/http://www.somalilandpress.com/ukip-supports-somaliland-national-day/|archive-date=26 June 2015}}</ref> This was followed by the Conservative UK government's official opening of a British Office in [[Hargeisa]], the capital of Somaliland. In 2020, the [[United Kingdom]], Denmark and the Netherlands approved four agreements with the government of Somaliland to improve critical infrastructure to support [[economic growth]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=UK, Denmark and Netherlands approve agreements with Somaliland Government on critical infrastructure to improve people's lives|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-denmark-and-netherlands-approve-agreements-with-somaliland-government-on-critical-infrastructure-to-improve-peoples-lives|access-date=7 July 2020}}</ref> In July 2019, the [[Birmingham City Council]] recognised the right to self-determination of Somaliland, becoming the 5th in Britain. On 4 July 2023, [[Gavin Williamson]] proposed a bill to the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] that would require the [[United Kingdom]] to recognise the [[Republic of Somaliland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politics.co.uk/parliament/gavin-williamson-introduces-bill-on-somaliland-recognition/|title=Gavin Williamson introduces Bill on Somaliland recognition|date=4 July 2023|work=Politics.co.uk|access-date=1 January 2024}}</ref>\n\n==Foreign minister==\n{{main|Minister of Foreign Affairs (Somaliland)}}\n\n[[File:Ahmed Mohamed Mohamoud Silanyo - Chatham House 2010.jpg|thumb|upright|400px|[[Ahmed Mahamoud Silanyo]], 4th President of the Republic of Somaliland, speaking at [[Chatham House]] in 2010.]]\nDr. [[Essa Kayd]] serves as the [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Somaliland)|Foreign Minister of Somaliland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/events/past-events/somaliland-s-foreign-minster-discusses-trade-and-recognition|title=Somaliland's Foreign Minister Discusses Trade and Recognition|last=Center|first=Africa|website=Atlantic Council|date=5 December 2018|language=en-gb|access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Diplomatic representative offices==\n{{Further|List of diplomatic missions of Somaliland|List of diplomatic missions in Somaliland}}\n\n===Liaison offices of Somaliland===\nSomaliland maintains representative (liaison) offices in several countries, but these missions do not have formal diplomatic status under the provisions of the [[Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations]].\n\nSuch offices exist in the following cities:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*{{flagicon|Ethiopia}} [[Addis Ababa]]<ref name=\"contactlist\">[http://www.somalilandgov.com/contacts.htm Contacts and addresses of the Somaliland Representative Offices around the world] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327105631/http://www.somalilandgov.com/contacts.htm |date=27 March 2010}}. Government of Somaliland.</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Djibouti}} [[Djibouti (city)|Djibouti City]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.embassypages.com/somaliland-representativeoffice-djiboutiville-djibouti|title=Representative Office of Somaliland in Djibouti Ville, Djibouti|access-date=22 July 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.consulate-info.com/consulate/31741/Somaliland-in-Djibouti-Ville | title=Somaliland Consulate in Djibouti Ville }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|UAE}} [[Dubai (city)|Dubai]], [[UAE]]<!--Dubai, not Abu Dhabi?--><!--<ref [http://www.somaliland.<ref [http://]. <-- Incorrect link!-->\n*{{flagicon|South Sudan}} [[Juba]], [[South Sudan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.embassypages.com/somalia-embassy-juba-southsudan|title=Embassy of Somalia in Juba, South Sudan|access-date=22 July 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.iconsular.com/office/Somaliland-in-Juba-in-South-Sudan | title=Consulate of Somaliland in Juba - South Sudan | access-date=10 June 2023 | archive-date=10 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230610135517/https://www.iconsular.com/office/Somaliland-in-Juba-in-South-Sudan }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[London]]<ref>[https://www.somaliland-mission.com/ Somaliland Mission UK] Retrieved 25 June 2020.</ref> ([[Mission of Somaliland, London|details]])\n*{{flagicon|Kenya}} [[Nairobi]]<ref name=\"contactlist\"/>\n*{{flagicon|Norway}} [[Oslo]]\n*{{flagicon|France}} [[Paris]]<ref>Wiren, Robert (8 April 2008). [http://www.lesnouvelles.org/P10_magazine/15_grandentretien/15055_mahamudsalahnur_eng.html France recognizes de facto Somaliland] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715224433/http://www.lesnouvelles.org/P10_magazine/15_grandentretien/15055_mahamudsalahnur_eng.html |date=15 July 2010}}. ''Les Nouvelles d'Addis''. Versailles. Retrieved 25 May 2010.</ref>\n*{{flagicon|South Africa}} [[Pretoria]]<ref>Somaliland Trade Liaison Office, Pretoria. [http://www.qarannews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7933&Itemid=291 Visit of Somaliland's UCID Foreign affairs spokesperson to south Africa]. Qaran News (1 May 2010). Retrieved 25 May 2010.</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Saudi Arabia}} [[Riyadh]]{{citation needed|date=May 2025}}\n*{{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Stockholm]]<ref>[http://www.somalilandembassy.se/ Somaliland Diplomatic Mission in Sweden] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510080355/http://www.somalilandembassy.se/ |date=10 May 2009}}. Somaliland Embassy in Sweden.</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Republic of China}} [[Taipei]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n*{{flagicon|Italy}} [[Torino|Turin]]<ref name=\"contactlist\"/>\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Washington D.C.]]<ref name=\"contactlist\"/>\n}}\n\n===Diplomatic offices of foreign countries in Somaliland===\nThe following foreign governments have diplomatic offices in [[Hargeisa]]:\n\n*{{flag|Denmark}} – Programme office\n*{{flag|Djibouti}} – Consulate; headed by a diplomat with the rank of consul general\n*{{flag|Ethiopia}} – [[Consulate]]; headed by a diplomat with the rank of [[ambassador]].<ref>[http://www.qarannews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6213&Itemid=59 Ethiopia's New Representative to Somaliland]. Qarannews (30 October 2009). Retrieved 25 May 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.icosgroup.net/modules/reports/chronic_failures_war_terror/somaliland Section II: Somaliland]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210211801/http://www.icosgroup.net/modules/reports/chronic_failures_war_terror/somaliland |date=10 December 2010}}. International Council on Security and Development. Retrieved 25 May 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://horseedmedia.net/2010/05/somalia-ethiopia-opens-consulate-in-puntland/ |title=SOMALIA: Ethiopia opens consulate in Puntland |publisher=Horseedmedia.net |date=29 May 2010 |access-date=29 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619101510/http://horseedmedia.net/2010/05/somalia-ethiopia-opens-consulate-in-puntland/ |archive-date=19 June 2010 }}</ref>\n*{{flag|Kenya}} – Liaison office<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/national/article/2001422784/kenya-somaliland-talks-bear-fruits-as-liaison-opened-in-hargeisa| title = Kenya, Somaliland talks bear fruits as liaison opened in Hargeisa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/bd/news/east-africa/kenya-liaison-office-somaliland-3541418 | title=Kenya names head of Liaison Office to Somaliland | date=7 September 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/tea/news/east-africa/kenya-liaison-office-somaliland-3541238| title = Kenya appoints head of Liaison Office to Somaliland - The East African| date = 7 September 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Isaac |first=Ongiri |date= 17 May 2014 |title=Kenya to open liaison office in Somaliland |url=http://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-to-open-liaison-office-in-Somaliland/-/1056/2318420/-/of7fpmz/-/index.html |newspaper=[[Daily Nation]] |access-date=13 October 2014}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Taiwan}} – [[Taiwan Representative Office in the Republic of Somaliland|Representative office]]\n*{{flag|Turkey}} – Consulate; headed by a diplomat with the rank of [[consul general]]\n*{{flag|UAE}} – Representative Office<ref>{{cite web |title=Somaliland president receives credentials from UAE envoy |url=https://www.bbc.com/somali/live/war-56384585 |website=[[BBC]] |access-date=7 May 2021 |date=13 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UAE Appoints a new representative to Somaliland |url=https://somalilandstandard.com/uae-appoints-a-new-representative-to-somaliland/ |website=Somaliland Standard |access-date=7 May 2021 |date=13 March 2021}}</ref>\n*{{flag|UK}} – Liaison office\n*{{flag|United States}} 2025  Lobbying Discussions and Media sources: Lobbying and media sources Hargeisa Representative office\n\n\nAs of February 2010,{{Fix|text=Out of date}} the [[Yemen]]i government is reportedly planning to open a diplomatic office in Hargeisa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://unpo.org/article/10743 |title=Somaliland: Yemen To Open Diplomatic Office in Somaliland |website=UNPO |date=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Yemen_and_Puntland_to_further_cooperation.shtml |title=Yemen and Puntland to further cooperation |publisher=Garoweonline.com |date=12 October 2010 |access-date=29 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328171433/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Yemen_and_Puntland_to_further_cooperation.shtml |archive-date=28 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Full Recognition as sovereign state==\n\nSomaliland has sought full international recognition as a [[sovereign state]] in the [[United Nations]] since the [[Somaliland War of Independence]]'s conclusion in 1991. Somaliland has diplomatic ties with many countries, including representative offices. Hargeisa told DNE Africa in a 2025 report that several countries, including the [[United States]], [[Israel]], and the [[United Arab Emirates]], are in the final stages of an agreement to grant official recognition to the country of Somaliland.\n\n[[File:Somaliland visa.jpg|thumb|Somaliland entry visa]]\n\n==Passports==\n{{main|Somaliland passport}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| width = 100\n| footer = \n| image1 = Somaliland Passport Cover.svg\n| caption1 = Regular Passport\n| image2 = Somaliland Service Passport.svg\n| caption2 = Service Passport\n| image3 = Somaliland Diplomatic Passport.svg\n| caption3 = Diplomatic Passport\n}}\n\nSomaliland issues its own [[passport]]s, recognised by certain nations. If and when Somaliland achieves its goal of recognition, a number of countries have stated that they will allow Somalilanders to travel to their countries, subject to visa regulations.{{Citation needed|reason=which countries?|date=December 2022}}\n\n==Organisational membership==\n\nSomaliland is a member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]] (UNPO).<ref name=\"unpo\"/>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of representative offices of Somaliland]]\n*[[List of diplomatic missions in Somaliland]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Somalia]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Foreign relations of Somaliland}}\n{{Foreign relations of states with limited recognition}}\n{{Foreign relations of the Commonwealth of Nations}}\n{{Africa in topic|Foreign relations of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreign Relations Of Somaliland}}\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Somaliland| ]]\n[[Category:Separatism in Somalia]]"